[^1]: Giving credit where it is due, Knuth claims his system is not all that new and is based on ideas that were generally floating around at the time. But he specifically mentions Pierre-Arnoul de Marneffe's Holon system, and "a somewhat similar system was independently created by Edwin Towster". You can read about the Holon programming in a survey compiled by the system's author. The survey includes in the foreward a letter Knuth had sent to de Marneffe complimenting him on his system, but also offering a critical take on its design. You can also read about Edwin Towster's system here.

[^2]: Knuth also invented TeX, a typesetting system that is widely used for producing high-quality documents, especially in the fields of mathematics and computer science. This was a time when many tools we use today were invented by necessity.